}{}$\gamma \in \mathbb {R}^+$\end{document} is the removal rate, and their ratio \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{wasysym} 
\usepackage{amsfonts} 
\usepackage{amssymb} 
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage{upgreek}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}
}{}$\mathcal {R}_0=\beta /\gamma$\end{document} is defined as the âbasic reproduction number." The rationale behind the first equation is that the number of new infections during an infinitesimal amount of time, âdS(u)/du, is equal to the number of susceptible people, S(u), times the product of the contact rate, I(t)/N, and the disease transmission rate Î². The third equation reflects that the infectious individuals leave the infectious population per unit time, dI(u)/du, at a rate of Î³I(u). The second equation follows immediately from the first and third equations as a result of dS(u)/du + dI(u)/du + dR(u)/du = 0. Assuming that only a small fraction of the population is infected or removed in the onset phase of an epidemic, we have S(u)/N â 1 and thus the second equation reduces to dI(u)/du = (Î² â Î³)I(u), revealing that the infectious population is growing if and only if Î² > Î³. As the expected lifetime of an infected case is given by Î³â1, the ratio \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
